{"title_page": "Cooper City, Florida", "text_new": "<!-- Infobox begins -->\n{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name            = Cooper City, Florida\n|settlement_type          = [[City (Florida)|City]]\n|nickname                 = \n|motto                    = Someplace Special\n|image_skyline            = Coopercity cityhall.jpg\n|imagesize                = \n|image_caption            = City hall\n|image_flag               = \n|flag_size                = \n|image_seal               = \n|seal_size                = \n|image_shield             = \n|shield_size              = \n|image_blank_emblem       = Cooper City municipal logo.png\n|blank_emblem_size        = \n|image_map                = Map of Florida highlighting Cooper City.svg\n|mapsize                  = 250x200px\n|map_caption              = \n|image_map1               = \n|mapsize1                 = \n|map_caption1             = \n|subdivision_type         = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_name         = {{nowrap|{{flag|United States of America}}}}\n|subdivision_type1        = [[U.S. state|State]]\n|subdivision_name1        = {{flag|Florida}}\n|subdivision_type2        = [[List of counties in Florida|County]]\n|subdivision_name2        = [[File:Logo of Broward County, Florida.svg|24px]] [[Broward County, Florida|Broward]]\n|government_type          = [[Council-Manager government|Commission-Manager]]\n|leader_title             = [[Mayor]]\n|leader_name              = Greg Ross\n|leader_title1            = [[City Council|Commissioners]]\n|leader_name1             = Howard Meltzer, Jeff Green, Massimo \"Max\" Pulcini, and James C. Curran  \n|leader_title2            = [[City Manager]]\n|leader_name2             = Joseph Napoli\n|leader_title3            = [[City Clerk]]\n|leader_name3             = Kathryn Sims\n|established_date         = \n|established_title2       = <!-- Incorporated (town) -->\n|established_date2        = \n|established_title3       = [[Municipal corporation|Incorporated]]\n|established_date3        = June 20, 1959<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.broward.org/PlanningAndRedevelopment/DemographicsAndEconomics/Documents/bbtn38.pdf |title=Broward-by-the-Numbers (pages 3-5) |publisher=www.broward.org |accessdate=2015-07-07 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151010175608/http://www.broward.org/PlanningAndRedevelopment/DemographicsAndEconomics/Documents/bbtn38.pdf |archivedate=2015-10-10 }}</ref>\n|area_magnitude           = \n|unit_pref                = Imperial\n|area_footnotes           = <ref name=\"CenPopGazetteer2016\">{{cite web|title=2018 U.S. Gazetteer Files|url=https://www2.census.gov/geo/docs/maps-data/data/gazetteer/2018_Gazetteer/2018_gaz_place_12.txt|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=Jul 19, 2019}}</ref>\n|area_total_km2           = 21.60\n|area_land_km2            = 20.82\n|area_water_km2           = 0.79\n|area_total_sq_mi         = 8.34\n|area_land_sq_mi          = 8.04\n|area_water_sq_mi         = 0.30\n|area_water_percent       = 3.63\n|area_metro_sq_mi         = \n|population_as_of         = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n|population_footnotes     = \n|population_note          = \n|population_total         = 28547\n|population_density_sq_mi = 4460.44\n|population_metro         = 5564635\n|population_density_metro_sq_mi   = \n|timezone                 = [[North American Eastern Time Zone|Eastern (EST)]]\n|utc_offset               = -5\n|timezone_DST             = EDT\n|utc_offset_DST           = -4\n|coordinates              = {{coord|26|2|41|N|80|17|22|W|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation_footnotes      = \n|elevation_m              = 2\n|elevation_ft             = 9\n|postal_code_type         = [[ZIP code]]\n|postal_code              = 33328-33330, 33026\n|area_code                = [[Area code 954|954]], [[Area code 754|754]]\n|website                  = {{URL|www.coopercityfl.org}}\n|blank_name               = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n|blank_info               = 12-14125<ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web |url=https://www.census.gov |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]] |accessdate=2008-01-31 |title=U.S. Census website }}</ref>\n|blank1_name              = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n|blank1_info              = 0280777<ref name=\"GR3\">{{cite web|url=http://geonames.usgs.gov|accessdate=2008-01-31|title=US Board on Geographic Names|publisher=[[United States Geological Survey]]|date=2007-10-25}}</ref>\n|footnotes                = \n|pop_est_as_of = 2018\n|pop_est_footnotes = <ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\"/>\n|population_est = 35853\n|population_density_km2 = 1722.28\n}}\n<!-- Infobox ends -->\n[[File:Sheriffs office cooper city 2017-08-06 (3).jpg|thumb|Sheriff's office]]\n'''Cooper City''' is a city in [[Broward County, Florida|Broward County]], [[Florida]], United States. The city is named for Morris Cooper, who founded the community in 1959. The city's population was 28,547 at the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]].<ref name=\"Census 2010\">{{cite web| url=http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_DP/G001/1600000US1214125| archive-url=https://archive.today/20200212182607/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_DP/G001/1600000US1214125| url-status=dead| archive-date=February 12, 2020| title=Geographic Identifiers: 2010 Demographic Profile Data (G001): Cooper City city, Florida| publisher=U.S. Census Bureau, American Factfinder| accessdate=October 21, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, with the annexation of the [[Waldrep Dairy Farm]], Cooper City started construction on the first major new home construction project within the past few decades. It was expected the addition of the {{convert|530|acre|km2|adj=on}} property would add upwards of 4,000 new residents through 2011.\n\nIn 2007, Cooper City was rated as one of the Best 10 Towns for Families by ''[[Family Circle]]'' magazine.<ref>[http://www.familycircle.com/family-fun/money/10-best-towns-for-families/]</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nCooper City is located at {{Coord|26.044631|-80.289566|type:city_region:US|format=dms|display=inline}}.<ref name=\"GR1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/geographies/reference-files/time-series/geo/gazetteer-files.html|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2011-04-23|date=2011-02-12|title=US Gazetteer files: 2010, 2000, and 1990}}</ref> The city is bounded by [[Davie, Florida|Davie]] to the north, [[Pembroke Pines, Florida|Pembroke Pines]] to the south, both [[Hollywood, Florida|Hollywood]] and Davie to the east, and [[Southwest Ranches, Florida|Southwest Ranches]] to the west.\n\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the city has a total area of {{convert|21.6|km2|order=flip}}, of which {{convert|20.8|km2|order=flip}} is land and {{Convert|0.8|km2|order=flip}} is water (3.63%).<ref name=\"Census 2010\"/>\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|1960= 550\n|1970= 2535\n|1980= 10140\n|1990= 20791\n|2000= 27939\n|2010= 28547\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=35853\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=June 4, 2019}}</ref>\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref name=\"DecennialCensus\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/decennial-census.html|title=Census of Population and Housing|publisher=Census.gov|accessdate=June 4, 2015}}</ref>\n}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"float: center; margin-right: 2em; width: 35%; font-size: 75%;\" \n!colspan=4|Cooper City Demographics\n|-\n![[United States Census, 2010|2010 Census]]||Cooper City||Broward County||Florida\n|-\n|Total population||28,547||1,748,066||18,801,310\n|-\n|Population, percent change, 2000 to 2010||+2.2%||+7.7%||+17.6%\n|-\n|Population density||3,551.1/sq&nbsp;mi||1,444.9/sq&nbsp;mi||350.6/sq&nbsp;mi\n|-\n|[[White (U.S. Census)|White or Caucasian]] (including [[White Hispanic]])||85.1%||63.1%||75.0%\n|-\n|([[Non-Hispanic Whites|Non-Hispanic White or Caucasian]])||65.1%||43.5%||57.9%\n|-\n|[[Black (U.S. Census)|Black or African-American]]||4.9%||26.7%||16.0%\n|-\n|[[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic or Latino (of any race)]]||22.8%||25.1%||22.5%\n|-\n|[[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]]||5.5%||3.2%||2.4%\n|-\n|[[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]] or [[Native Alaskan]]||0.3%||0.3%||0.4%\n|-\n|[[Pacific Islander (U.S. Census)|Pacific Islander]] or [[Native Hawaiian]]||0.0%||0.1%||0.1%\n|-\n|[[Multiracial American|Two or more races (Multiracial)]]||2.4%||2.9%||2.5%\n|-\n|[[Other races (U.S. Census)|Some Other Race]]||1.8%||3.7%||3.6%\n|}\n\nAs of 2010, there were 9,912 households out of which 2.9% were vacant. In 2000, 51.5% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 70.8% were married couples living together, 11.9% had a female householder with no husband present, and 14.2% were non-families. 10.8% of all households were made up of individuals and 3.1% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 3.06 and the average family size was 3.30.\n\nIn 2000, the city the population was spread out with 31.3% under the age of 18, 6.3% from 18 to 24, 30.2% from 25 to 44, 25.5% from 45 to 64, and 6.7% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 37 years. For every 100 females, there were 94.1 males. For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 88.8 males.\n\nIn 2000, the median income for a household in the city was $75,166, and the median income for a family was $78,172. Males had a median income of $51,931 versus $33,788 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the city was $27,474. About 2.9% of families and 3.2% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 3.2% of those under age 18 and 4.7% of those age 65 or over.\n\nAs of 2000, [[English language|English]] was spoken as a [[first language]] by 78.55% of the population, while [[Spanish language|Spanish]] was spoken by 15.08%, and [[Hebrew language|Hebrew]] speakers made up 1.25% of all residents. Other [[mother tongue]]s included languages such as both [[French language|French]] and [[Malayalam language|Malayalam]] making up 0.75% of residents, as well as [[Italian language|Italian]] being at 0.69%, while [[Chinese language|Chinese]] was at 0.59%.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mla.org/map_data_results&state_id=12&county_id=&mode=place&zip=&place_id=14125&cty_id=&ll=&a=&ea=&order=r |title=MLA Data Center results for Cooper City, FL |publisher=[[Modern Language Association]] |accessdate=2007-09-22}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2000, Cooper City had the sixty-fifth highest percentage of [[Cuba]]n residents in the US, at 5.29% of the city's population (tied with [[West Palm Beach, Florida|West Palm Beach]],)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.epodunk.com/ancestry/Cuban.html |title=Ancestry Map of Cuban Communities |publisher=Epodunk.com |accessdate=2007-10-25}}</ref> and it had the ninety-second highest percentage of [[Colombia]]n residents in the US, which made up 1.78% of all residents (tied with [[Pinecrest, Florida|Pinecrest]] and [[South Bound Brook, New Jersey]].)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.epodunk.com/ancestry/Colombian.html |title=Ancestry Map of Colombian Communities |publisher=Epodunk.com |accessdate=2007-10-25}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\n===Elementary schools===\n* '''Cooper City Elementary''' has attained an \"A\" rating for 2018/2019.\n* '''Embassy Creek Elementary''' is an [[elementary school]] located in Cooper City that teaches grades [[Kindergarten|K]]-[[Fifth grade|5]]. The school is a member of the [[Broward School District]]. It is an \"A\" school and is currently ranked number 36 out of about 3000 schools in the state of Florida for 2011. It is named after its nearby developments of Embassy Lakes and Rock Creek.\n* '''Griffin Elementary School''' is an elementary school located in Cooper City which teaches grades [[Kindergarten|K]]-[[Fifth grade|5]]. The school has also attained an \"A\" rating for 2018/2019.\n\n===Middle schools===\n* '''Pioneer Middle School''' is a [[middle school]] located in Cooper City that teaches grades [[Sixth grade|6]]-[[Eighth grade|8]]. Pioneer Middle School was rated the number 2 middle school in Broward County, and number 55 in the State out of 583 schools in the state of Florida for 2011. The school has maintained an \"A\" rating since the Florida Department of Education began grading schools in the late 1990s.<ref>http://www.fldoe.org/accountability/accountability-reporting/school-grades/archives.stml</ref>\n\n===High school===\n{{unreferenced section|date=July 2019}}\n* '''[[Cooper City High School]]''' has attained an \"A\" rating for 2018/2019. It is currently ranked among the top ten percent schools in America. It is the number 46 [[High school (North America)|high school]] in Florida and one of the top schools in Broward County. It serves students from [[Ninth grade|9]]-[[Twelfth grade|12]]. Cooper City High offers more than twenty-two AP classes. The AP participation in Cooper City is 48%, which makes it  one of the highest AP participation schools in Broward county.\n\n===Private schools===\n*'''Potential Christian Academy''' (formerly Flamingo Road Christian Academy) is the school ministry of Potential Church. Established in 1983 as a preschool program, PCA has grown to include Pre-K1 to 8th grade. On October 10, 2010 the school changed its name to Potential Christian Academy from Flamingo Road Christian Academy.<ref>http://ilovepca.com/</ref>\n* '''Franklin Academy''' is a public charter school serving students in kindergarten through eighth grade.\n*'''Nur-ul Islam Academy''' is a private Islamic school located in Cooper City, founded in 1996. It serves students from Pre-K to 12th grade.\n\n==Sports==\n[[File:Sportscomplex cooper city 2017-08-06 (5).jpg|thumb|Cooper City Sports Park]]\n[[Brian Piccolo Park]] in Cooper City is the location of a cricket grounds, and in 2004 played host to [[first-class cricket]] when the [[United States cricket team]] played [[Canadian cricket team|Canada]] in the [[ICC Intercontinental Cup]]. It also served as the home ground for the [[Florida Thunder]] [[Pro Cricket]] team in 2004. The park is also home to one of the few cycling tracks in South Florida. The park also encompasses a skateboard park. There are two other parks in Cooper City and they are Bill Lips and Cooper City Optimist. Cooper City Optimist and is where most of everything takes place and Bill lips is a neighborhood park with a recreational softball team.\n\nCooper City is also the birthplace of [[Troy State]] defensive end Ken Wagner, who was a part of their National Championship team in the late 1980s.\n\nFormer Miami Dolphins place kicker Olindo Mare graduated from Cooper City High School in 1991.\n\n==Notable people==\n* Skai Moore, [[Linebacker]], [[University of South Carolina]] <ref>[http://www.gamecocksonline.com/sports/m-footbl/mtt/skai_moore_854512.html Skai Moore - Gamecocks Player Profile]</ref>\n* [[Rick Shaw (radio)|Rick Shaw]], radio [[disc jockey]] ([[WQAM]]), lived there.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/local/broward/fl-reg-rick-shaw-obit-20170922-story.html |title=Legendary South Florida DJ Rick Shaw dies at 78 |newspaper=[[Sun-Sentinel]] |date=September 22, 2017}}</ref>\n*[[Eric Hosmer]], current first-baseman for the San Diego Padres and former first-baseman for the Kansas City Royals.\n*[[Fortunate Sons]], An expeditionary group who made the fastest coast to coast drive in a family sedan in 2015. \n*[[Pujj Hossain]], Bollywood fashion expert.\n\n==Sister city==\n* {{Flagicon|Ireland}} '''[[Killarney]]''', [[Ireland]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.coopercityfl.org Cooper City official website]\n\n{{Broward County, Florida}}\n{{Miami metropolitan area}}\n{{Greater Miami}}\n{{Florida}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Cities in Broward County, Florida]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1959]]\n[[Category:Cities in Florida]]\n", "text_old": "<!-- Infobox begins -->\n{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name            = Cooper City, Florida\n|settlement_type          = [[City (Florida)|City]]\n|nickname                 = \n|motto                    = Someplace Special\n|image_skyline            = Coopercity cityhall.jpg\n|imagesize                = \n|image_caption            = City hall\n|image_flag               = \n|flag_size                = \n|image_seal               = \n|seal_size                = \n|image_shield             = \n|shield_size              = \n|image_blank_emblem       = Cooper City municipal logo.png\n|blank_emblem_size        = \n|image_map                = Map of Florida highlighting Cooper City.svg\n|mapsize                  = 250x200px\n|map_caption              = \n|image_map1               = \n|mapsize1                 = \n|map_caption1             = \n|subdivision_type         = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_name         = {{nowrap|{{flag|United States of America}}}}\n|subdivision_type1        = [[U.S. state|State]]\n|subdivision_name1        = {{flag|Florida}}\n|subdivision_type2        = [[List of counties in Florida|County]]\n|subdivision_name2        = [[File:Logo of Broward County, Florida.svg|24px]] [[Broward County, Florida|Broward]]\n|government_type          = [[Council-Manager government|Commission-Manager]]\n|leader_title             = [[Mayor]]\n|leader_name              = Greg Ross\n|leader_title1            = [[City Council|Commissioners]]\n|leader_name1             = Howard Meltzer, Jeff Green, Massimo \"Max\" Pulcini, and James C. Curran  \n|leader_title2            = [[City Manager]]\n|leader_name2             = Joseph Napoli\n|leader_title3            = [[City Clerk]]\n|leader_name3             = Kathryn Sims\n|established_date         = \n|established_title2       = <!-- Incorporated (town) -->\n|established_date2        = \n|established_title3       = [[Municipal corporation|Incorporated]]\n|established_date3        = June 20, 1959<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.broward.org/PlanningAndRedevelopment/DemographicsAndEconomics/Documents/bbtn38.pdf |title=Broward-by-the-Numbers (pages 3-5) |publisher=www.broward.org |accessdate=2015-07-07 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151010175608/http://www.broward.org/PlanningAndRedevelopment/DemographicsAndEconomics/Documents/bbtn38.pdf |archivedate=2015-10-10 }}</ref>\n|area_magnitude           = \n|unit_pref                = Imperial\n|area_footnotes           = <ref name=\"CenPopGazetteer2016\">{{cite web|title=2018 U.S. Gazetteer Files|url=https://www2.census.gov/geo/docs/maps-data/data/gazetteer/2018_Gazetteer/2018_gaz_place_12.txt|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=Jul 19, 2019}}</ref>\n|area_total_km2           = 21.60\n|area_land_km2            = 20.82\n|area_water_km2           = 0.79\n|area_total_sq_mi         = 8.34\n|area_land_sq_mi          = 8.04\n|area_water_sq_mi         = 0.30\n|area_water_percent       = 3.63\n|area_metro_sq_mi         = \n|population_as_of         = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n|population_footnotes     = \n|population_note          = \n|population_total         = 28547\n|population_density_sq_mi = 4460.44\n|population_metro         = 5564635\n|population_density_metro_sq_mi   = \n|timezone                 = [[North American Eastern Time Zone|Eastern (EST)]]\n|utc_offset               = -5\n|timezone_DST             = EDT\n|utc_offset_DST           = -4\n|coordinates              = {{coord|26|2|41|N|80|17|22|W|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation_footnotes      = \n|elevation_m              = 2\n|elevation_ft             = 9\n|postal_code_type         = [[ZIP code]]\n|postal_code              = 33328-33330, 33026\n|area_code                = [[Area code 954|954]], [[Area code 754|754]]\n|website                  = {{URL|www.coopercityfl.org}}\n|blank_name               = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n|blank_info               = 12-14125<ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web |url=https://www.census.gov |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]] |accessdate=2008-01-31 |title=U.S. Census website }}</ref>\n|blank1_name              = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n|blank1_info              = 0280777<ref name=\"GR3\">{{cite web|url=http://geonames.usgs.gov|accessdate=2008-01-31|title=US Board on Geographic Names|publisher=[[United States Geological Survey]]|date=2007-10-25}}</ref>\n|footnotes                = \n|pop_est_as_of = 2018\n|pop_est_footnotes = <ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\"/>\n|population_est = 35853\n|population_density_km2 = 1722.28\n}}\n<!-- Infobox ends -->\n[[File:Sheriffs office cooper city 2017-08-06 (3).jpg|thumb|Sheriff's office]]\n'''Cooper City''' is a city in [[Broward County, Florida|Broward County]], [[Florida]], United States. The city is named for Morris Cooper, who founded the community in 1959. The city's population was 28,547 at the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]].<ref name=\"Census 2010\">{{cite web| url=http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_DP/G001/1600000US1214125| archive-url=https://archive.today/20200212182607/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_DP/G001/1600000US1214125| url-status=dead| archive-date=February 12, 2020| title=Geographic Identifiers: 2010 Demographic Profile Data (G001): Cooper City city, Florida| publisher=U.S. Census Bureau, American Factfinder| accessdate=October 21, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, with the annexation of the [[Waldrep Dairy Farm]], Cooper City started construction on the first major new home construction project within the past few decades. It was expected the addition of the {{convert|530|acre|km2|adj=on}} property would add upwards of 4,000 new residents through 2011.\n\nIn 2007, Cooper City was rated as one of the Best 10 Towns for Families by ''[[Family Circle]]'' magazine.<ref>[http://www.familycircle.com/family-fun/money/10-best-towns-for-families/]</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nCooper City is located at {{Coord|26.044631|-80.289566|type:city_region:US|format=dms|display=inline}}.<ref name=\"GR1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/geographies/reference-files/time-series/geo/gazetteer-files.html|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2011-04-23|date=2011-02-12|title=US Gazetteer files: 2010, 2000, and 1990}}</ref> The city is bounded by [[Davie, Florida|Davie]] to the north, [[Pembroke Pines, Florida|Pembroke Pines]] to the south, both [[Hollywood, Florida|Hollywood]] and Davie to the east, and [[Southwest Ranches, Florida|Southwest Ranches]] to the west.\n\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the city has a total area of {{convert|21.6|km2|order=flip}}, of which {{convert|20.8|km2|order=flip}} is land and {{Convert|0.8|km2|order=flip}} is water (3.63%).<ref name=\"Census 2010\"/>\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|1960= 550\n|1970= 2535\n|1980= 10140\n|1990= 20791\n|2000= 27939\n|2010= 28547\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=35853\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=June 4, 2019}}</ref>\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref name=\"DecennialCensus\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/decennial-census.html|title=Census of Population and Housing|publisher=Census.gov|accessdate=June 4, 2015}}</ref>\n}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"float: center; margin-right: 2em; width: 35%; font-size: 75%;\" \n!colspan=4|Cooper City Demographics\n|-\n![[United States Census, 2010|2010 Census]]||Cooper City||Broward County||Florida\n|-\n|Total population||28,547||1,748,066||18,801,310\n|-\n|Population, percent change, 2000 to 2010||+2.2%||+7.7%||+17.6%\n|-\n|Population density||3,551.1/sq&nbsp;mi||1,444.9/sq&nbsp;mi||350.6/sq&nbsp;mi\n|-\n|[[White (U.S. Census)|White or Caucasian]] (including [[White Hispanic]])||85.1%||63.1%||75.0%\n|-\n|([[Non-Hispanic Whites|Non-Hispanic White or Caucasian]])||65.1%||43.5%||57.9%\n|-\n|[[Black (U.S. Census)|Black or African-American]]||4.9%||26.7%||16.0%\n|-\n|[[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic or Latino (of any race)]]||22.8%||25.1%||22.5%\n|-\n|[[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]]||5.5%||3.2%||2.4%\n|-\n|[[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]] or [[Native Alaskan]]||0.3%||0.3%||0.4%\n|-\n|[[Pacific Islander (U.S. Census)|Pacific Islander]] or [[Native Hawaiian]]||0.0%||0.1%||0.1%\n|-\n|[[Multiracial American|Two or more races (Multiracial)]]||2.4%||2.9%||2.5%\n|-\n|[[Other races (U.S. Census)|Some Other Race]]||1.8%||3.7%||3.6%\n|}\n\nAs of 2010, there were 9,912 households out of which 2.9% were vacant. In 2000, 51.5% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 70.8% were married couples living together, 11.9% had a female householder with no husband present, and 14.2% were non-families. 10.8% of all households were made up of individuals and 3.1% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 3.06 and the average family size was 3.30.\n\nIn 2000, the city the population was spread out with 31.3% under the age of 18, 6.3% from 18 to 24, 30.2% from 25 to 44, 25.5% from 45 to 64, and 6.7% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 37 years. For every 100 females, there were 94.1 males. For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 88.8 males.\n\nIn 2000, the median income for a household in the city was $75,166, and the median income for a family was $78,172. Males had a median income of $51,931 versus $33,788 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the city was $27,474. About 2.9% of families and 3.2% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 3.2% of those under age 18 and 4.7% of those age 65 or over.\n\nAs of 2000, [[English language|English]] was spoken as a [[first language]] by 78.55% of the population, while [[Spanish language|Spanish]] was spoken by 15.08%, and [[Hebrew language|Hebrew]] speakers made up 1.25% of all residents. Other [[mother tongue]]s included languages such as both [[French language|French]] and [[Malayalam language|Malayalam]] making up 0.75% of residents, as well as [[Italian language|Italian]] being at 0.69%, while [[Chinese language|Chinese]] was at 0.59%.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mla.org/map_data_results&state_id=12&county_id=&mode=place&zip=&place_id=14125&cty_id=&ll=&a=&ea=&order=r |title=MLA Data Center results for Cooper City, FL |publisher=[[Modern Language Association]] |accessdate=2007-09-22}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2000, Cooper City had the sixty-fifth highest percentage of [[Cuba]]n residents in the US, at 5.29% of the city's population (tied with [[West Palm Beach, Florida|West Palm Beach]],)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.epodunk.com/ancestry/Cuban.html |title=Ancestry Map of Cuban Communities |publisher=Epodunk.com |accessdate=2007-10-25}}</ref> and it had the ninety-second highest percentage of [[Colombia]]n residents in the US, which made up 1.78% of all residents (tied with [[Pinecrest, Florida|Pinecrest]] and [[South Bound Brook, New Jersey]].)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.epodunk.com/ancestry/Colombian.html |title=Ancestry Map of Colombian Communities |publisher=Epodunk.com |accessdate=2007-10-25}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\n===Elementary schools===\n* '''Cooper City Elementary''' has attained an \"A\" rating for 2018/2019.\n* '''Embassy Creek Elementary''' is an [[elementary school]] located in Cooper City that teaches grades [[Kindergarten|K]]-[[Fifth grade|5]]. The school is a member of the [[Broward School District]]. It is an \"A\" school and is currently ranked number 36 out of about 3000 schools in the state of Florida for 2011. It is named after its nearby developments of Embassy Lakes and Rock Creek.\n* '''Griffin Elementary School''' is an elementary school located in Cooper City which teaches grades [[Kindergarten|K]]-[[Fifth grade|5]]. The school has also attained an \"A\" rating for 2018/2019.\n\n===Middle schools===\n* '''Pioneer Middle School''' is a [[middle school]] located in Cooper City that teaches grades [[Sixth grade|6]]-[[Eighth grade|8]]. Pioneer Middle School was rated the number 2 middle school in Broward County, and number 55 in the State out of 583 schools in the state of Florida for 2011. The school has maintained an \"A\" rating since the Florida Department of Education began grading schools in the late 1990s.<ref>http://www.fldoe.org/accountability/accountability-reporting/school-grades/archives.stml</ref>\n\n===High school===\n{{unreferenced section|date=July 2019}}\n* '''[[Cooper City High School]]''' has attained an \"A\" rating for 2018/2019. It is currently ranked among one of the top ten percent schools in America. It is the number 46 [[High school (North America)|high school]] in Florida and one of the top schools in Broward County. It serves students from [[Ninth grade|9]]-[[Twelfth grade|12]]. Cooper City High offers more than twenty-two AP classes. The AP participation in Cooper City is 48%, which makes it  one of the highest AP participation schools in Broward county.\n\n===Private schools===\n*'''Potential Christian Academy''' (formerly Flamingo Road Christian Academy) is the school ministry of Potential Church. Established in 1983 as a preschool program, PCA has grown to include Pre-K1 to 8th grade. On October 10, 2010 the school changed its name to Potential Christian Academy from Flamingo Road Christian Academy.<ref>http://ilovepca.com/</ref>\n* '''Franklin Academy''' is a public charter school serving students in kindergarten through eighth grade.\n*'''Nur-ul Islam Academy''' is a private Islamic school located in Cooper City, founded in 1996. It serves students from Pre-K to 12th grade.\n\n==Sports==\n[[File:Sportscomplex cooper city 2017-08-06 (5).jpg|thumb|Cooper City Sports Park]]\n[[Brian Piccolo Park]] in Cooper City is the location of a cricket grounds, and in 2004 played host to [[first-class cricket]] when the [[United States cricket team]] played [[Canadian cricket team|Canada]] in the [[ICC Intercontinental Cup]]. It also served as the home ground for the [[Florida Thunder]] [[Pro Cricket]] team in 2004. The park is also home to one of the few cycling tracks in South Florida. The park also encompasses a skateboard park. There are two other parks in Cooper City and they are Bill Lips and Cooper City Optimist. Cooper City Optimist and is where most of everything takes place and Bill lips is a neighborhood park with a recreational softball team.\n\nCooper City is also the birthplace of [[Troy State]] defensive end Ken Wagner, who was a part of their National Championship team in the late 1980s.\n\nFormer Miami Dolphins place kicker Olindo Mare graduated from Cooper City High School in 1991.\n\n==Notable people==\n* Skai Moore, [[Linebacker]], [[University of South Carolina]] <ref>[http://www.gamecocksonline.com/sports/m-footbl/mtt/skai_moore_854512.html Skai Moore - Gamecocks Player Profile]</ref>\n* [[Rick Shaw (radio)|Rick Shaw]], radio [[disc jockey]] ([[WQAM]]), lived there.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/local/broward/fl-reg-rick-shaw-obit-20170922-story.html |title=Legendary South Florida DJ Rick Shaw dies at 78 |newspaper=[[Sun-Sentinel]] |date=September 22, 2017}}</ref>\n*[[Eric Hosmer]], current first-baseman for the San Diego Padres and former first-baseman for the Kansas City Royals.\n*[[Fortunate Sons]], An expeditionary group who made the fastest coast to coast drive in a family sedan in 2015. \n*[[Pujj Hossain]], Bollywood fashion expert.\n\n==Sister city==\n* {{Flagicon|Ireland}} '''[[Killarney]]''', [[Ireland]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.coopercityfl.org Cooper City official website]\n\n{{Broward County, Florida}}\n{{Miami metropolitan area}}\n{{Greater Miami}}\n{{Florida}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Cities in Broward County, Florida]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1959]]\n[[Category:Cities in Florida]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Reword - you can't be \"among one\"", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cooper_City,_Florida"}
{"title_page": "Florence Pugh", "text_new": "{{Short description|English actress}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               =\n| image              = Florence Pugh in 2020 (2) (cropped).jpg\n| caption            = Pugh in 2020\n| birth_name         =\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1996|1|3}}\n| birth_place        = [[Oxford]], [[Oxfordshire]], England\n| occupation         = Actress\n| years_active       = 2014\u2013present\n| relatives          = [[Toby Sebastian]] (brother)\n| awards             = [[List of awards and nominations received by Florence Pugh|Full list]]\n}}\n'''Florence <!--Don't put Rose here by itself--> Pugh'''{{efn|Records show her name to be Florence Rose C. M. Pugh;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:QVHX-HGKS|title=FamilySearch}}</ref> the second and third middle names are not currently known to the public.}} ({{IPAc-en|p|j|u\u02d0}} {{respell|PEW}}; born 3 January 1996) is an English actress. She made her professional acting debut in the mystery film ''[[The Falling (2014 film)|The Falling]]'' (2014) and gained recognition for her leading role as an unhappily married woman in the independent drama ''[[Lady Macbeth (film)|Lady Macbeth]]'' (2016). Her performance in the latter won her the [[BIFA Award for Best Performance by an Actress in a British Independent Film|BIFA Award for Best Actress]]. She also drew critical praise for her leading role in the miniseries ''[[The Little Drummer Girl (miniseries)|The Little Drummer Girl]]'' (2018).\n\nPugh's international breakthrough came in 2019, during which she garnered positive reviews for her portrayals of wrestler [[Paige (wrestler)|Paige]] in the biographical sports film ''[[Fighting with My Family]]'', an emotionally troubled woman in the horror film ''[[Midsommar (film)|Midsommar]]'', and [[Amy March]] in the coming-of-age period film ''[[Little Women (2019 film)|Little Women]]''. For the lattermost, she received [[Academy Award]] and [[BAFTA Award]] nominations.\n\n==Early life==\nPugh was born on 3 January 1996<ref name=EmpireProf>{{cite web |title=Florence Pugh |url=https://www.empireonline.com/people/florence-pugh-2/ |newspaper=[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]] |accessdate=2 February 2020|date=15 August 2015 }}</ref> in [[Oxford]].<ref name=BBC201704>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-37274640|title=Lady Macbeth: Florence Pugh on her killer first lead role|date=28 April 2017|last=Masters|first=Tim|publisher=BBC News|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170320004457/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-37274640|archivedate=20 March 2017}}</ref> Her father, Clinton Pugh, is a restaurateur in Oxford,<ref name=OxfordTimes>{{cite web|last1=MacAlister|first1=Katherine|title=Florence Pugh goes straight from A-levels to LA|url=http://www.oxfordtimes.co.uk/leisure/focus/12909725.Florence_Pugh_goes_straight_from_A_levels_to_LA/|website=The Oxford Times|accessdate=26 December 2015|date=23 April 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151227152431/http://www.oxfordtimes.co.uk/leisure/focus/12909725.Florence_Pugh_goes_straight_from_A_levels_to_LA/|archivedate=27 December 2015}}</ref> while her mother, Deborah, is a dancer and dance teacher.<ref name=Inews201704>{{cite news|url=https://inews.co.uk/essentials/florence-pugh-dying-not-bad/|work=The I|date=27 April 2017|last=Aftab|first=Kaleem|title=Florence Pugh: 'Dying was not that bad'|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170917171141/https://inews.co.uk/essentials/florence-pugh-dying-not-bad/|archivedate=17 September 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Grdn201810\">{{cite news |last1=Hayes |first1=Martha |title=Florence Pugh: 'You never see an unplucked brow in Hollywood' |url=https://www.theguardian.com/fashion/tvandradioblog/2018/oct/06/florence-pugh-lady-macbeth-king-lear-le-carre |accessdate=21 October 2018 |publisher=The Guardian |date=6 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181020221431/https://www.theguardian.com/fashion/tvandradioblog/2018/oct/06/florence-pugh-lady-macbeth-king-lear-le-carre |archive-date=20 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Pugh has three siblings: actor and musician [[Toby Sebastian]], actress Arabella Gibbins, and youngest sibling Rafaela \"Raffie\" Pugh.<ref name=\"Grdn201810\"/><ref name=Vogue202001>{{cite web |last=Wood |first=Gaby |date=9 January 2020 |title=From Little Women to Marvel Superhero, Florence Pugh Is a New Kind of Breakout Star |url=https://www.vogue.com/article/florence-pugh-cover-february-2020 |newspaper=[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]] |accessdate=2 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nPugh suffered from [[tracheomalacia]] as a child and was frequently hospitalized. When she was three, the family relocated to [[Andalusia]] in southern [[Spain]], hoping the warmer weather would improve her health. Pugh lived in [[Sotogrande]] until the age of six, when the family moved back to Oxfordshire.<ref name=Vogue202001/><ref name=Elle202001>{{cite web |last=Wood |first=Gaby |date=20 January 2020 |title=Florence Pugh es la actriz del momento tras su nominaci\u00f3n a un Oscar por 'Mujercitas' |url=https://www.elle.com/es/star-style/noticias-famosos/a30528725/florence-pugh-oscar-mujercitas-peliculas-instagram-youtube/ |newspaper=[[Elle (magazine)|Elle]] |accessdate=2 February 2020 |language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\nPugh's love of accents and comedy was first displayed at age six, when she played [[Mary, mother of Jesus|Mary]] in a school [[nativity play]] with a Yorkshire accent.<ref name=\"Grdn201810\"/> She was privately educated at [[Wychwood School]] and at [[St. Edward's School, Oxford]], <ref name=Inews201704/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/showbiz/celebrity-news/go-westeros-meet-game-of-thrones-new-player-toby-sebastian-10119623.html|title=Go Westeros: meet Game of Thrones' new player Toby Sebastian|work=London Evening Standard|date=19 March 2015|last=Fishwick|first=Samuel|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151015164442/http://www.standard.co.uk/showbiz/celebrity-news/go-westeros-meet-game-of-thrones-new-player-toby-sebastian-10119623.html|archivedate=15 October 2015}}</ref> but says the schools did not support her acting ambitions: \"For a long time it was like, \u2018I know these people don\u2019t back me\u2019, because they didn\u2019t.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hayes |first1=Martha |title=Florence Pugh: \u2018You never see an unplucked brow in Hollywood' |url=https://www.theguardian.com/fashion/tvandradioblog/2018/oct/06/florence-pugh-lady-macbeth-king-lear-le-carre |accessdate=9 April 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=6 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===2014\u20132018: Career beginnings===\n[[File:Florence Pugh at the 58th BFI London Film Festival Awards (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright|left|Pugh at the 2014 [[BFI London Film Festival]]]]\nWhile still in school, Pugh made her professional acting debut in the mystery drama ''[[The Falling (2014 film)|The Falling]]'' (2014), in which she played a precocious teenager opposite [[Maisie Williams]].<ref name=\"Grdn201810\" /><ref>{{cite news|last1=Orr|first1=Gillian|title='After you left the room I said, Wow!': director Carol Morley and actress Florence Pugh on their haunting new film The Falling|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/features/after-you-left-the-room-i-said-wow-director-carol-morley-and-actress-florence-pugh-on-their-haunting-10182952.html|work=The Independent|accessdate=26 December 2015|date=18 April 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151219042448/http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/features/after-you-left-the-room-i-said-wow-director-carol-morley-and-actress-florence-pugh-on-their-haunting-10182952.html|archivedate=19 December 2015}}</ref> Tara Brady of ''[[The Irish Times]]'' called her \"remarkable\" and Mike McCahill of ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' said she conveyed her character's \"teen-queen bearing with the vulnerability of one still unsure of her own body\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/culture/film/the-falling-review-combining-kitchen-sink-grit-and-otherworldly-mystery-1.2186468|title=The Falling review: combining kitchen-sink grit and otherworldly mystery|work=The Irish Times|first=Tara|last=Brady|date=23 April 2015|accessdate=7 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151219011554/http://www.irishtimes.com/culture/film/the-falling-review-combining-kitchen-sink-grit-and-otherworldly-mystery-1.2186468|archive-date=19 December 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>\n{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/film/the-falling/review/|title=The Falling review: 'potently suggestive'|work=The Daily Telegraph|first=Mike|last=McCahill|date=24 April 2015|accessdate=7 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180827075423/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/film/the-falling/review/|archive-date=27 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In the same year, Pugh was nominated for Best British Newcomer at the [[BFI London Film Festival]] and for Best Young British/Irish performer by the [[London Film Critics' Circle]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Carol leads the nominations for the 36th London Critics' Circle Film Awards|url=http://www.criticscircle.org.uk/film/?ID=470|publisher=London Film Critics Circle|date=15 December 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151219221153/http://www.criticscircle.org.uk/film/?ID=470|archivedate=19 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nPugh made her American television debut in the television film ''Studio City'', co-starring [[Eric McCormack]], in 2015.<ref name=\"Grdn201810\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/tv/news/studio-city-fox-cast-florence-pugh-eric-mccormack-daughter-1201447167/|title=British Newcomer Florence Pugh Cast as Eric McCormack's Daughter in 'Studio City'|work=Variety|first=Elizabeth|last=Wagmeister|date=5 March 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180114020504/https://variety.com/2015/tv/news/studio-city-fox-cast-florence-pugh-eric-mccormack-daughter-1201447167/|archivedate=14 January 2018}}</ref> The next year, she starred in the independent drama ''[[Lady Macbeth (film)|Lady Macbeth]]'' and had a recurring role as a [[webcam model]] in the first season of the [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] detective series ''[[Marcella (TV series)|Marcella]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-37274640|title=Lady Macbeth: Florence Pugh on her killer first lead role|publisher=BBC News|first=Tim|last=Masters|date=28 April 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170320004457/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-37274640|archivedate=20 March 2017}}</ref> In the former, based on the novella ''[[Lady Macbeth of the Mtsensk District (novella)|Lady Macbeth of the Mtsensk District]]'' by [[Nikolai Leskov]], she played a young girl unhappily married to a much older man. Reviewing the film for ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'', Guy Lodge called Pugh a \"a major talent to watch\" and praised her portrayal of her character's \"complex, under-the-skin transformation\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/reviews/lady-macbeth-review-1201853847/|title=Film Review: 'Lady Macbeth'|author=Lodge, Guy|date=9 September 2016|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=21 July 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170710055050/http://variety.com/2016/film/reviews/lady-macbeth-review-1201853847/|archive-date=10 July 2017}}</ref> For her performance, she won the [[BIFA Award for Best Performance by an Actress in a British Independent Film]], among others.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/gods-own-country-bifa-1202635435/|title='God's Own Country' Wins Big at British Independent Film Awards|author=Clarke, Stewart|date=10 December 2017|work=Variety|accessdate=6 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180811232130/https://variety.com/2017/film/news/gods-own-country-bifa-1202635435/|archive-date=11 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Pugh appeared in the action film ''[[The Commuter (film)|The Commuter]]'' and played [[Cordelia (King Lear)|Cordelia]] to [[Anthony Hopkins]]'s [[Leir of Britain]] in [[Richard Eyre]]'s television film ''[[King Lear (2018 film)|King Lear]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.screendaily.com/news/first-look-at-anthony-hopkins-florence-pugh-in-bbcs-king-lear/5127717.article|title=First look at Anthony Hopkins, Florence Pugh in BBC's 'King Lear'|work=Screen Daily|first=Ben|last=Dalton|date=22 March 2018|accessdate=7 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180907221333/https://www.screendaily.com/news/first-look-at-anthony-hopkins-florence-pugh-in-bbcs-king-lear/5127717.article|archive-date=7 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Later that year, she portrayed [[Elizabeth de Burgh]] in the [[Netflix]] historical film ''[[Outlaw King]]'' (2018), which also stars [[Chris Pine]] as [[Robert the Bruce]]. Charles Bramesco of ''[[The Guardian]]'' found her \"excellent despite her thankless role\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/sep/07/outlaw-king-review-chris-pine|title=Outlaw King review \u2013 Chris Pine fronts up for some macho medieval bombast|work=The Guardian|first=Charles|last=Bramesco|date=7 September 2018|accessdate=7 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180907111009/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/sep/07/outlaw-king-review-chris-pine|archive-date=7 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> She next appeared in a [[The Little Drummer Girl (miniseries)|six-part miniseries]] adaptation of [[John le Carr\u00e9]]'s spy novel ''[[The Little Drummer Girl]]'', in which she played an actress in the 1970s who becomes embroiled in an espionage plot.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://deadline.com/2018/08/john-le-carres-the-little-drummer-girl-miniseries-gets-november-premiere-date-on-amc-1202449266/|title=John le Carr\u00e9's 'The Little Drummer Girl' Miniseries Gets November Premiere Date On AMC|work=Deadline Hollywood|first=Denise|last=Petsky|date=21 August 2018|accessdate=7 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180826232520/https://deadline.com/2018/08/john-le-carres-the-little-drummer-girl-miniseries-gets-november-premiere-date-on-amc-1202449266/|archive-date=26 August 2018|url-status=live}}\n</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Meet the cast of The Little Drummer Girl |url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/tv/2018-11-02/the-little-drummer-girl-bbc-cast-florence-pugh-alexander-skarsgard-michael-shannon/ |work=Radio Times |access-date=7 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181106005026/https://www.radiotimes.com/news/tv/2018-11-02/the-little-drummer-girl-bbc-cast-florence-pugh-alexander-skarsgard-michael-shannon/ |archive-date=6 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> In a mixed review of the series, Richard Lawson of ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'' wrote, \"Pugh is terrific throughout, once again asserting her star-on-the-rise status. She smartly mixes earthiness with sophistication, wisdom with na\u00efvet\u00e9.\"<ref>{{cite news |author=Lawson, Richard|title=Florence Pugh Proves Herself a Star in The Little Drummer Girl |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2018/11/the-little-drummer-girl-review-florence-pugh-park-chan-wook |accessdate=22 January 2019 |work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]] |date=13 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2019\u2013present: Breakthrough===\n[[File:Florence Pugh by Gage Skidmore.jpg|thumb|upright|Pugh at the 2019 [[San Diego Comic-Con]] promoting ''[[Black Widow (2020 film)|Black Widow]]'']]\nPugh was listed on ''[[Forbes]]''{{'}} annual [[Forbes 30 Under 30|30 Under 30]] list, which recognises the 30 most influential people in Europe under the age of 30, in 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.harpersbazaar.com/uk/celebrities/news/a26301510/30-under-30-forbes-list/|website=Harper's Bazaar|title=Lily James, Jodie Comer and Letitia Wright named among the most game-changing under 30-year-olds in Europe|last=Blair|first=Olivia|date=12 February 2019}}</ref> She was also recognised as having a breakthrough in the same year, during which she starred in three major films.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/2019-breakthrough-entertainer-florence-pugh-owns-the-year/2019/12/16/86799f64-2036-11ea-b034-de7dc2b5199b_story.html|title=2019 Breakthrough Entertainer: Florence Pugh owns the year|last=Myers|first=Amanda Lee|date=16 December 2019|work=The Washington Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/12/florence-pugh-little-women-black-widow-midsommar-fighting-with-my-family-interview-1202799412/|title=How To Hit A Grand Slam: Florence Pugh On Her Banner Roll 'Fighting With My Family', 'Midsommar', 'Little Women' & 'Black Widow'|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro|date=5 December 2019|accessdate=10 December 2019}}</ref> She first starred as professional wrestler [[Paige (wrestler)|Paige]] in ''[[Fighting with My Family]]'', a comedy-drama about Paige's relationship with her family, co-starring [[Lena Headey]] and [[Dwayne Johnson]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/dwayne-johnson-gets-ring-fighting-my-family-wrestling-film-starring-florence-pugh-972551|title=Dwayne Johnson Gets in the Ring for 'Fighting with My Family' Wrestling Film (Exclusive)|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|first1=Rebecca|last1=Ford|first2=Alex|last2=Ritman|date=7 February 2017|accessdate=22 February 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170216140352/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/dwayne-johnson-gets-ring-fighting-my-family-wrestling-film-starring-florence-pugh-972551|archivedate=16 February 2017}}</ref> The film premiered at the [[2019 Sundance Film Festival]] to critical acclaim.<ref>\n{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/01/dwayne-johnson-fighting-with-my-family-sundance-film-festival-surprise-screening-1202524984/|title=Dwayne Johnson & Dany Garcia's Seven Bucks/MGM Pic 'Fighting With My Family' Making World Premiere At Sundance As Surprise Screening|first1=Anthony|last1=D'Alessandro|date=11 January 2019|publisher=|accessdate=23 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190116041845/https://deadline.com/2019/01/dwayne-johnson-fighting-with-my-family-sundance-film-festival-surprise-screening-1202524984/|archive-date=16 January 2019|url-status=live}}\n</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/fighting_with_my_family|title=Fighting with My Family (2019)|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=26 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190116071238/https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/fighting_with_my_family|archive-date=16 January 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Geoffrey Macnab of ''[[The Independent]]'' noted how different the role was from Pugh's previous appearances, and wrote that she was \"completely convincing as the wrestler\" and that she showed \"the same defiance, scruffy glamour and self-deprecating humour as the real life [...] Paige.\"<ref>{{cite news |author=Macnab, Geoffrey |title=Fighting with My Family review: Far more gripping than its subject matter might suggest |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/reviews/fighting-with-my-family-review-film-movie-wwe-stephen-merchant-florence-pugh-wrestling-a8800111.html |accessdate=7 March 2019 |work=[[The Independent]] |date=1 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190303235132/https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/reviews/fighting-with-my-family-review-film-movie-wwe-stephen-merchant-florence-pugh-wrestling-a8800111.html |archive-date=3 March 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> She next played the lead role in [[Ari Aster]]'s horror film ''[[Midsommar (film)|Midsommar]]'', which chronicles a troubled couple who encounter Swedish cultists. [[David Edelstein]] of ''[[New York (magazine)|Vulture]]'' called her performance \"amazingly vivid\" and wrote, \"Her face is so wide and open that she seems to have nowhere to hide her emotions.\"<ref name=vulture>{{cite web|work=[[New York (magazine)|Vulture]]|last=Edelstein|first=David|date=19 June 2019|url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/06/midsommar-review-ari-asters-ambitious-blurry-horror-trip.html|title=Ari Aster's Midsommar Is an Ambitious, Blurry Horror Trip|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190619220438/https://www.vulture.com/2019/06/midsommar-review-ari-asters-ambitious-blurry-horror-trip.html|archive-date=19 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn her final film release of 2019, Pugh played Amy March, a headstrong artist, in [[Greta Gerwig]]'s [[Little Women (2019 film)|adaptation]] of [[Louisa May Alcott]]'s novel ''[[Little Women]]'' to critical acclaim.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/little-women-emma-watson-star-greta-gerwig-feature-1137420|title=Emma Watson in Talks to Join Meryl Streep in 'Little Women'|work=The Hollywood Reporter|access-date=26 August 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180826183045/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/little-women-emma-watson-star-greta-gerwig-feature-1137420|archive-date=26 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The cast rehearsed the script for two weeks before filming began, but Pugh was not able to participate as she was filming ''Midsommar'' at the time. She stated that she believed this helped create distance between her and her co-stars playing her sisters, which proved conducive for her character's personality.<ref>{{cite news|last=Kaufman|first=Amy|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/movies/story/2019-10-31/little-women-saoirse-ronan-florence-pugh|title=How Saoirse Ronan and Florence Pugh updated 'Little Women' for modern feminists|work=Los Angeles Times|date=31 October 2019|accessdate=9 December 2019}}</ref> Highlighting Pugh's performance, David Rooney of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' wrote that she \"continues to prove herself a distinctive talent, managing all the tricky contradictions of the role with disarming grace, humor and a willful streak that grows almost imperceptibly into wisdom.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Rooney|first=David|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/little-women-1257699|title='Little Women': Film Review|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=25 November 2019|accessdate=9 December 2019}}</ref> The film earned over $203 million against its $40 million budget.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/title/tt3281548/?ref_=bo_se_r_1|title=Little Women (2019)|website=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=2 March 2020}}</ref> Pugh's portrayal of March earned her nominations for the [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress]] and the [[BAFTA Award for Best Actress in a Supporting Role]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Ritman|first=Alex|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/bafta-awards-2020-nominations-unveiled-1267114|title='Joker' Leads BAFTA 2020 Nominations|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=6 January 2020|access-date=7 January 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Oscar\">{{cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/culture/2020/1/13/21060660/oscar-nominees-2020-full-list|last1=Abad-Santos|first1=Alex|last2=Wilkinson|first2=Alissa|website=Vox|date=13 January 2020|title=Oscars 2020: the full list of nominees}}</ref>\n\nPugh will next star alongside [[Scarlett Johansson]] in the [[Marvel Cinematic Universe]] film ''[[Black Widow (2020 film)|Black Widow]]'', about the [[Natasha Romanoff (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|titular superhero]], as another agent of the Black Widow program, [[Black Widow (Yelena Belova)|Yelena Belova]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/florence-pugh-scarlett-johansson-black-widow-1203165665/|title=Scarlett Johansson's 'Black Widow' Movie Adds Florence Pugh|last=Kroll|first=Justin|work=Variety|date=18 March 2019|accessdate=18 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/comic-con/2019/07/20/black-widow-movie-first-look-scarlett-johansson/|title=Black Widow hits Comic-Con with first details of Scarlett Johansson film|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|first=Devan|last=Coggan|date=20 July 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190721020135/https://ew.com/comic-con/2019/07/20/black-widow-movie-first-look-scarlett-johansson/|archivedate=21 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nSince April 2019, Pugh has been in a relationship with American actor [[Zach Braff]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/dating/florence-pugh-zach-braff-age-gap-relationship-dating-instagram-a9263991.html|title=Florence Pugh defends 21-year age gap with boyfriend Zach Braff|website=The Independent|date=30 December 2019|last=Young|first=Sarah}}</ref> As of January 2020, she resides in [[London]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/lifestyle/esmagazine/get-to-know-little-womens-florence-pugh-a4315651.html|title=Little Women's Florence Pugh on her new role, Meryl Streep and women in Hollywood|website=The Evening Standard|date=17 December 2019|last=Dove|first=Rachael}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/08/movies/florence-pugh-little-women.html|title=Florence Pugh's True Hollywood Fairy Tale|work=The New York Times|last=Ugwu|first=Reggie|date=8 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\"|Notes\n|-\n|2014\n|''[[The Falling (2014 film)|The Falling]]''\n|Abbie Mortimer\n|\n|-\n|2016\n|''[[Lady Macbeth (film)|Lady Macbeth]]''\n|Katherine Lester\n|\n|-\n|2018\n|''[[The Commuter (film)|The Commuter]]''\n|Gwen\n|\n|-\n|2018\n|''[[Outlaw King]]''\n|[[Elizabeth de Burgh]]\n|\n|-\n|2018\n|''[[Malevolent (2018 film)|Malevolent]]''\n|Angela Sayers\n|\n|-\n|2019\n|''[[Fighting with My Family]]''\n|[[Paige (wrestler)|Saraya \"Paige\" Knight]]\n|\n|-\n|2019\n| ''[[Midsommar (film)|Midsommar]]''\n| Dani Ardor\n|\n|-\n|2019\n| ''[[Little Women (2019 film)|Little Women]]''\n| [[Amy March]]\n|\n|-\n|2020\n|''[[Black Widow (2020 film)|Black Widow]]''\n| [[Black Widow (Yelena Belova)|Yelena Belova / Black Widow]]\n| Post-production\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\"|Notes\n|-\n|2015\n|''Studio City''\n|Cat\n|Unaired TV pilot\n|-\n|2016\n|''[[Marcella (TV series)|Marcella]]''\n|Cara Thomas\n|3 episodes\n|-\n|2018\n|''[[King Lear (2018 film)|King Lear]]''\n|[[Cordelia (King Lear)|Cordelia]]\n|Television film\n|-\n|2018\n|''[[The Little Drummer Girl (miniseries)|The Little Drummer Girl]]''\n|Charmian \"Charlie\" Ross\n|Miniseries\n|}\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{{main|List of awards and nominations received by Florence Pugh}}\n\nPugh has received nominations for an [[Academy Awards|Academy Award]], two [[British Academy Film Awards]], and two [[Critics' Choice Movie Awards]].\n\nPugh won the British Independent Film Award for Best Actress for her performance in ''Lady Macbeth'' (2016). For her role in ''Midsommar'' (2019), she was nominated for the [[Gotham Independent Film Award for Best Actress]]. For her performance in ''Little Women'' (2019), she received nominations for the BAFTA Award for Best Actress in a Supporting Role and the Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress.\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Florence Pugh}}\n* {{IMDb name}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title = [[List of awards and nominations received by Florence Pugh|Awards for Florence Pugh]]\n|list = \n{{BIFA Award for Best Performance by an Actress in a British Independent Film}}\n{{London Film Critics Circle Award for British Actress of the Year}}\n{{Troph\u00e9e Chopard}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pugh, Florence}}\n[[Category:1996 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century English actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Oxfordshire]]\n[[Category:English film actresses]]\n[[Category:People from Oxford]]\n[[Category:People educated at St Edward's School, Oxford]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|English actress}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               =\n| image              = Florence Pugh in 2020 (2) (cropped).jpg\n| caption            = Pugh in 2020\n| birth_name         =\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1996|1|3}}\n| birth_place        = [[Oxford]], [[Oxfordshire]], England\n| occupation         = Actress\n| years_active       = 2014\u2013present\n| relatives          = [[Toby Sebastian]] (brother)\n| awards             = [[List of awards and nominations received by Florence Pugh|Full list]]\n}}\n'''Florence <!--Don't put Rose here by itself--> Pugh'''{{efn|Records show her name to be Florence Rose C. M. Pugh;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:QVHX-HGKS|title=FamilySearch}}</ref> the second and third middle names are not currently known to the public.}} ({{IPAc-en|p|j|u\u02d0}} {{respell|PEW}}; born 3 January 1996) is an English actress. She made her professional acting debut in the mystery film ''[[The Falling (2014 film)|The Falling]]'' (2014) and gained recognition for her leading role as an unhappily married woman in the independent drama ''[[Lady Macbeth (film)|Lady Macbeth]]'' (2016). Her performance in the latter won her the [[BIFA Award for Best Performance by an Actress in a British Independent Film|BIFA Award for Best Actress]]. She also drew critical praise for her leading role in the miniseries ''[[The Little Drummer Girl (miniseries)|The Little Drummer Girl]]'' (2018).\n\nPugh's international breakthrough came in 2019, during which she garnered positive reviews for her portrayals of wrestler [[Paige (wrestler)|Paige]] in the biographical sports film ''[[Fighting with My Family]]'', an emotionally troubled woman in the horror film ''[[Midsommar (film)|Midsommar]]'', and [[Amy March]] in the coming-of-age period film ''[[Little Women (2019 film)|Little Women]]''. For the lattermost, she received [[Academy Award]] and [[BAFTA Award]] nominations.\n\n==Early life==\nPugh was born on 3 January 1996<ref name=EmpireProf>{{cite web |title=Florence Pugh |url=https://www.empireonline.com/people/florence-pugh-2/ |newspaper=[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]] |accessdate=2 February 2020|date=15 August 2015 }}</ref> in [[Oxford]].<ref name=BBC201704>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-37274640|title=Lady Macbeth: Florence Pugh on her killer first lead role|date=28 April 2017|last=Masters|first=Tim|publisher=BBC News|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170320004457/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-37274640|archivedate=20 March 2017}}</ref> Her father, Clinton Pugh, is a restaurateur in Oxford,<ref name=OxfordTimes>{{cite web|last1=MacAlister|first1=Katherine|title=Florence Pugh goes straight from A-levels to LA|url=http://www.oxfordtimes.co.uk/leisure/focus/12909725.Florence_Pugh_goes_straight_from_A_levels_to_LA/|website=The Oxford Times|accessdate=26 December 2015|date=23 April 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151227152431/http://www.oxfordtimes.co.uk/leisure/focus/12909725.Florence_Pugh_goes_straight_from_A_levels_to_LA/|archivedate=27 December 2015}}</ref> while her mother, Deborah, is a dancer and dance teacher.<ref name=Inews201704>{{cite news|url=https://inews.co.uk/essentials/florence-pugh-dying-not-bad/|work=The I|date=27 April 2017|last=Aftab|first=Kaleem|title=Florence Pugh: 'Dying was not that bad'|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170917171141/https://inews.co.uk/essentials/florence-pugh-dying-not-bad/|archivedate=17 September 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Grdn201810\">{{cite news |last1=Hayes |first1=Martha |title=Florence Pugh: 'You never see an unplucked brow in Hollywood' |url=https://www.theguardian.com/fashion/tvandradioblog/2018/oct/06/florence-pugh-lady-macbeth-king-lear-le-carre |accessdate=21 October 2018 |publisher=The Guardian |date=6 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181020221431/https://www.theguardian.com/fashion/tvandradioblog/2018/oct/06/florence-pugh-lady-macbeth-king-lear-le-carre |archive-date=20 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Pugh has three siblings: actor and musician [[Toby Sebastian]], actress Arabella Gibbins, and youngest sibling Rafaela \"Raffie\" Pugh.<ref name=\"Grdn201810\"/><ref name=Vogue202001>{{cite web |last=Wood |first=Gaby |date=9 January 2020 |title=From Little Women to Marvel Superhero, Florence Pugh Is a New Kind of Breakout Star |url=https://www.vogue.com/article/florence-pugh-cover-february-2020 |newspaper=[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]] |accessdate=2 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nPugh suffered from [[tracheomalacia]] as a child and was frequently hospitalized. When she was three, the family relocated to [[Andalusia]] in southern [[Spain]], hoping the warmer weather would improve her health. Pugh lived in [[Sotogrande]] until the age of six, when the family moved back to Oxfordshire.<ref name=Vogue202001/><ref name=Elle202001>{{cite web |last=Wood |first=Gaby |date=20 January 2020 |title=Florence Pugh es la actriz del momento tras su nominaci\u00f3n a un Oscar por 'Mujercitas' |url=https://www.elle.com/es/star-style/noticias-famosos/a30528725/florence-pugh-oscar-mujercitas-peliculas-instagram-youtube/ |newspaper=[[Elle (magazine)|Elle]] |accessdate=2 February 2020 |language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\nPugh's love of accents and comedy was first displayed at age six, when she played [[Mary, mother of Jesus|Mary]] in a school [[nativity play]] with a Yorkshire accent.<ref name=\"Grdn201810\"/> She was privately educated at [[Wychwood School]] and at [[St Edward's School, Oxford]], <ref name=Inews201704/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/showbiz/celebrity-news/go-westeros-meet-game-of-thrones-new-player-toby-sebastian-10119623.html|title=Go Westeros: meet Game of Thrones' new player Toby Sebastian|work=London Evening Standard|date=19 March 2015|last=Fishwick|first=Samuel|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151015164442/http://www.standard.co.uk/showbiz/celebrity-news/go-westeros-meet-game-of-thrones-new-player-toby-sebastian-10119623.html|archivedate=15 October 2015}}</ref> but says the schools did not support her acting ambitions: \"For a long time it was like, \u2018I know these people don\u2019t back me\u2019, because they didn\u2019t.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hayes |first1=Martha |title=Florence Pugh: \u2018You never see an unplucked brow in Hollywood' |url=https://www.theguardian.com/fashion/tvandradioblog/2018/oct/06/florence-pugh-lady-macbeth-king-lear-le-carre |accessdate=9 April 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=6 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===2014\u20132018: Career beginnings===\n[[File:Florence Pugh at the 58th BFI London Film Festival Awards (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright|left|Pugh at the 2014 [[BFI London Film Festival]]]]\nWhile still in school, Pugh made her professional acting debut in the mystery drama ''[[The Falling (2014 film)|The Falling]]'' (2014), in which she played a precocious teenager opposite [[Maisie Williams]].<ref name=\"Grdn201810\" /><ref>{{cite news|last1=Orr|first1=Gillian|title='After you left the room I said, Wow!': director Carol Morley and actress Florence Pugh on their haunting new film The Falling|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/features/after-you-left-the-room-i-said-wow-director-carol-morley-and-actress-florence-pugh-on-their-haunting-10182952.html|work=The Independent|accessdate=26 December 2015|date=18 April 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151219042448/http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/features/after-you-left-the-room-i-said-wow-director-carol-morley-and-actress-florence-pugh-on-their-haunting-10182952.html|archivedate=19 December 2015}}</ref> Tara Brady of ''[[The Irish Times]]'' called her \"remarkable\" and Mike McCahill of ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' said she conveyed her character's \"teen-queen bearing with the vulnerability of one still unsure of her own body\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/culture/film/the-falling-review-combining-kitchen-sink-grit-and-otherworldly-mystery-1.2186468|title=The Falling review: combining kitchen-sink grit and otherworldly mystery|work=The Irish Times|first=Tara|last=Brady|date=23 April 2015|accessdate=7 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151219011554/http://www.irishtimes.com/culture/film/the-falling-review-combining-kitchen-sink-grit-and-otherworldly-mystery-1.2186468|archive-date=19 December 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>\n{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/film/the-falling/review/|title=The Falling review: 'potently suggestive'|work=The Daily Telegraph|first=Mike|last=McCahill|date=24 April 2015|accessdate=7 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180827075423/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/film/the-falling/review/|archive-date=27 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In the same year, Pugh was nominated for Best British Newcomer at the [[BFI London Film Festival]] and for Best Young British/Irish performer by the [[London Film Critics' Circle]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Carol leads the nominations for the 36th London Critics' Circle Film Awards|url=http://www.criticscircle.org.uk/film/?ID=470|publisher=London Film Critics Circle|date=15 December 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151219221153/http://www.criticscircle.org.uk/film/?ID=470|archivedate=19 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nPugh made her American television debut in the television film ''Studio City'', co-starring [[Eric McCormack]], in 2015.<ref name=\"Grdn201810\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/tv/news/studio-city-fox-cast-florence-pugh-eric-mccormack-daughter-1201447167/|title=British Newcomer Florence Pugh Cast as Eric McCormack's Daughter in 'Studio City'|work=Variety|first=Elizabeth|last=Wagmeister|date=5 March 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180114020504/https://variety.com/2015/tv/news/studio-city-fox-cast-florence-pugh-eric-mccormack-daughter-1201447167/|archivedate=14 January 2018}}</ref> The next year, she starred in the independent drama ''[[Lady Macbeth (film)|Lady Macbeth]]'' and had a recurring role as a [[webcam model]] in the first season of the [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] detective series ''[[Marcella (TV series)|Marcella]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-37274640|title=Lady Macbeth: Florence Pugh on her killer first lead role|publisher=BBC News|first=Tim|last=Masters|date=28 April 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170320004457/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-37274640|archivedate=20 March 2017}}</ref> In the former, based on the novella ''[[Lady Macbeth of the Mtsensk District (novella)|Lady Macbeth of the Mtsensk District]]'' by [[Nikolai Leskov]], she played a young girl unhappily married to a much older man. Reviewing the film for ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'', Guy Lodge called Pugh a \"a major talent to watch\" and praised her portrayal of her character's \"complex, under-the-skin transformation\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/reviews/lady-macbeth-review-1201853847/|title=Film Review: 'Lady Macbeth'|author=Lodge, Guy|date=9 September 2016|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=21 July 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170710055050/http://variety.com/2016/film/reviews/lady-macbeth-review-1201853847/|archive-date=10 July 2017}}</ref> For her performance, she won the [[BIFA Award for Best Performance by an Actress in a British Independent Film]], among others.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/gods-own-country-bifa-1202635435/|title='God's Own Country' Wins Big at British Independent Film Awards|author=Clarke, Stewart|date=10 December 2017|work=Variety|accessdate=6 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180811232130/https://variety.com/2017/film/news/gods-own-country-bifa-1202635435/|archive-date=11 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Pugh appeared in the action film ''[[The Commuter (film)|The Commuter]]'' and played [[Cordelia (King Lear)|Cordelia]] to [[Anthony Hopkins]]'s [[Leir of Britain]] in [[Richard Eyre]]'s television film ''[[King Lear (2018 film)|King Lear]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.screendaily.com/news/first-look-at-anthony-hopkins-florence-pugh-in-bbcs-king-lear/5127717.article|title=First look at Anthony Hopkins, Florence Pugh in BBC's 'King Lear'|work=Screen Daily|first=Ben|last=Dalton|date=22 March 2018|accessdate=7 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180907221333/https://www.screendaily.com/news/first-look-at-anthony-hopkins-florence-pugh-in-bbcs-king-lear/5127717.article|archive-date=7 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Later that year, she portrayed [[Elizabeth de Burgh]] in the [[Netflix]] historical film ''[[Outlaw King]]'' (2018), which also stars [[Chris Pine]] as [[Robert the Bruce]]. Charles Bramesco of ''[[The Guardian]]'' found her \"excellent despite her thankless role\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/sep/07/outlaw-king-review-chris-pine|title=Outlaw King review \u2013 Chris Pine fronts up for some macho medieval bombast|work=The Guardian|first=Charles|last=Bramesco|date=7 September 2018|accessdate=7 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180907111009/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/sep/07/outlaw-king-review-chris-pine|archive-date=7 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> She next appeared in a [[The Little Drummer Girl (miniseries)|six-part miniseries]] adaptation of [[John le Carr\u00e9]]'s spy novel ''[[The Little Drummer Girl]]'', in which she played an actress in the 1970s who becomes embroiled in an espionage plot.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://deadline.com/2018/08/john-le-carres-the-little-drummer-girl-miniseries-gets-november-premiere-date-on-amc-1202449266/|title=John le Carr\u00e9's 'The Little Drummer Girl' Miniseries Gets November Premiere Date On AMC|work=Deadline Hollywood|first=Denise|last=Petsky|date=21 August 2018|accessdate=7 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180826232520/https://deadline.com/2018/08/john-le-carres-the-little-drummer-girl-miniseries-gets-november-premiere-date-on-amc-1202449266/|archive-date=26 August 2018|url-status=live}}\n</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Meet the cast of The Little Drummer Girl |url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/tv/2018-11-02/the-little-drummer-girl-bbc-cast-florence-pugh-alexander-skarsgard-michael-shannon/ |work=Radio Times |access-date=7 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181106005026/https://www.radiotimes.com/news/tv/2018-11-02/the-little-drummer-girl-bbc-cast-florence-pugh-alexander-skarsgard-michael-shannon/ |archive-date=6 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> In a mixed review of the series, Richard Lawson of ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'' wrote, \"Pugh is terrific throughout, once again asserting her star-on-the-rise status. She smartly mixes earthiness with sophistication, wisdom with na\u00efvet\u00e9.\"<ref>{{cite news |author=Lawson, Richard|title=Florence Pugh Proves Herself a Star in The Little Drummer Girl |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2018/11/the-little-drummer-girl-review-florence-pugh-park-chan-wook |accessdate=22 January 2019 |work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]] |date=13 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2019\u2013present: Breakthrough===\n[[File:Florence Pugh by Gage Skidmore.jpg|thumb|upright|Pugh at the 2019 [[San Diego Comic-Con]] promoting ''[[Black Widow (2020 film)|Black Widow]]'']]\nPugh was listed on ''[[Forbes]]''{{'}} annual [[Forbes 30 Under 30|30 Under 30]] list, which recognises the 30 most influential people in Europe under the age of 30, in 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.harpersbazaar.com/uk/celebrities/news/a26301510/30-under-30-forbes-list/|website=Harper's Bazaar|title=Lily James, Jodie Comer and Letitia Wright named among the most game-changing under 30-year-olds in Europe|last=Blair|first=Olivia|date=12 February 2019}}</ref> She was also recognised as having a breakthrough in the same year, during which she starred in three major films.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/2019-breakthrough-entertainer-florence-pugh-owns-the-year/2019/12/16/86799f64-2036-11ea-b034-de7dc2b5199b_story.html|title=2019 Breakthrough Entertainer: Florence Pugh owns the year|last=Myers|first=Amanda Lee|date=16 December 2019|work=The Washington Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/12/florence-pugh-little-women-black-widow-midsommar-fighting-with-my-family-interview-1202799412/|title=How To Hit A Grand Slam: Florence Pugh On Her Banner Roll 'Fighting With My Family', 'Midsommar', 'Little Women' & 'Black Widow'|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro|date=5 December 2019|accessdate=10 December 2019}}</ref> She first starred as professional wrestler [[Paige (wrestler)|Paige]] in ''[[Fighting with My Family]]'', a comedy-drama about Paige's relationship with her family, co-starring [[Lena Headey]] and [[Dwayne Johnson]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/dwayne-johnson-gets-ring-fighting-my-family-wrestling-film-starring-florence-pugh-972551|title=Dwayne Johnson Gets in the Ring for 'Fighting with My Family' Wrestling Film (Exclusive)|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|first1=Rebecca|last1=Ford|first2=Alex|last2=Ritman|date=7 February 2017|accessdate=22 February 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170216140352/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/dwayne-johnson-gets-ring-fighting-my-family-wrestling-film-starring-florence-pugh-972551|archivedate=16 February 2017}}</ref> The film premiered at the [[2019 Sundance Film Festival]] to critical acclaim.<ref>\n{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/01/dwayne-johnson-fighting-with-my-family-sundance-film-festival-surprise-screening-1202524984/|title=Dwayne Johnson & Dany Garcia's Seven Bucks/MGM Pic 'Fighting With My Family' Making World Premiere At Sundance As Surprise Screening|first1=Anthony|last1=D'Alessandro|date=11 January 2019|publisher=|accessdate=23 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190116041845/https://deadline.com/2019/01/dwayne-johnson-fighting-with-my-family-sundance-film-festival-surprise-screening-1202524984/|archive-date=16 January 2019|url-status=live}}\n</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/fighting_with_my_family|title=Fighting with My Family (2019)|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=26 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190116071238/https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/fighting_with_my_family|archive-date=16 January 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Geoffrey Macnab of ''[[The Independent]]'' noted how different the role was from Pugh's previous appearances, and wrote that she was \"completely convincing as the wrestler\" and that she showed \"the same defiance, scruffy glamour and self-deprecating humour as the real life [...] Paige.\"<ref>{{cite news |author=Macnab, Geoffrey |title=Fighting with My Family review: Far more gripping than its subject matter might suggest |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/reviews/fighting-with-my-family-review-film-movie-wwe-stephen-merchant-florence-pugh-wrestling-a8800111.html |accessdate=7 March 2019 |work=[[The Independent]] |date=1 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190303235132/https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/reviews/fighting-with-my-family-review-film-movie-wwe-stephen-merchant-florence-pugh-wrestling-a8800111.html |archive-date=3 March 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> She next played the lead role in [[Ari Aster]]'s horror film ''[[Midsommar (film)|Midsommar]]'', which chronicles a troubled couple who encounter Swedish cultists. [[David Edelstein]] of ''[[New York (magazine)|Vulture]]'' called her performance \"amazingly vivid\" and wrote, \"Her face is so wide and open that she seems to have nowhere to hide her emotions.\"<ref name=vulture>{{cite web|work=[[New York (magazine)|Vulture]]|last=Edelstein|first=David|date=19 June 2019|url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/06/midsommar-review-ari-asters-ambitious-blurry-horror-trip.html|title=Ari Aster's Midsommar Is an Ambitious, Blurry Horror Trip|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190619220438/https://www.vulture.com/2019/06/midsommar-review-ari-asters-ambitious-blurry-horror-trip.html|archive-date=19 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn her final film release of 2019, Pugh played Amy March, a headstrong artist, in [[Greta Gerwig]]'s [[Little Women (2019 film)|adaptation]] of [[Louisa May Alcott]]'s novel ''[[Little Women]]'' to critical acclaim.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/little-women-emma-watson-star-greta-gerwig-feature-1137420|title=Emma Watson in Talks to Join Meryl Streep in 'Little Women'|work=The Hollywood Reporter|access-date=26 August 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180826183045/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/little-women-emma-watson-star-greta-gerwig-feature-1137420|archive-date=26 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The cast rehearsed the script for two weeks before filming began, but Pugh was not able to participate as she was filming ''Midsommar'' at the time. She stated that she believed this helped create distance between her and her co-stars playing her sisters, which proved conducive for her character's personality.<ref>{{cite news|last=Kaufman|first=Amy|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/movies/story/2019-10-31/little-women-saoirse-ronan-florence-pugh|title=How Saoirse Ronan and Florence Pugh updated 'Little Women' for modern feminists|work=Los Angeles Times|date=31 October 2019|accessdate=9 December 2019}}</ref> Highlighting Pugh's performance, David Rooney of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' wrote that she \"continues to prove herself a distinctive talent, managing all the tricky contradictions of the role with disarming grace, humor and a willful streak that grows almost imperceptibly into wisdom.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Rooney|first=David|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/little-women-1257699|title='Little Women': Film Review|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=25 November 2019|accessdate=9 December 2019}}</ref> The film earned over $203 million against its $40 million budget.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/title/tt3281548/?ref_=bo_se_r_1|title=Little Women (2019)|website=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=2 March 2020}}</ref> Pugh's portrayal of March earned her nominations for the [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress]] and the [[BAFTA Award for Best Actress in a Supporting Role]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Ritman|first=Alex|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/bafta-awards-2020-nominations-unveiled-1267114|title='Joker' Leads BAFTA 2020 Nominations|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=6 January 2020|access-date=7 January 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Oscar\">{{cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/culture/2020/1/13/21060660/oscar-nominees-2020-full-list|last1=Abad-Santos|first1=Alex|last2=Wilkinson|first2=Alissa|website=Vox|date=13 January 2020|title=Oscars 2020: the full list of nominees}}</ref>\n\nPugh will next star alongside [[Scarlett Johansson]] in the [[Marvel Cinematic Universe]] film ''[[Black Widow (2020 film)|Black Widow]]'', about the [[Natasha Romanoff (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|titular superhero]], as another agent of the Black Widow program, [[Black Widow (Yelena Belova)|Yelena Belova]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/florence-pugh-scarlett-johansson-black-widow-1203165665/|title=Scarlett Johansson's 'Black Widow' Movie Adds Florence Pugh|last=Kroll|first=Justin|work=Variety|date=18 March 2019|accessdate=18 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/comic-con/2019/07/20/black-widow-movie-first-look-scarlett-johansson/|title=Black Widow hits Comic-Con with first details of Scarlett Johansson film|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|first=Devan|last=Coggan|date=20 July 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190721020135/https://ew.com/comic-con/2019/07/20/black-widow-movie-first-look-scarlett-johansson/|archivedate=21 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nSince April 2019, Pugh has been in a relationship with American actor [[Zach Braff]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/dating/florence-pugh-zach-braff-age-gap-relationship-dating-instagram-a9263991.html|title=Florence Pugh defends 21-year age gap with boyfriend Zach Braff|website=The Independent|date=30 December 2019|last=Young|first=Sarah}}</ref> As of January 2020, she resides in [[London]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/lifestyle/esmagazine/get-to-know-little-womens-florence-pugh-a4315651.html|title=Little Women's Florence Pugh on her new role, Meryl Streep and women in Hollywood|website=The Evening Standard|date=17 December 2019|last=Dove|first=Rachael}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/08/movies/florence-pugh-little-women.html|title=Florence Pugh's True Hollywood Fairy Tale|work=The New York Times|last=Ugwu|first=Reggie|date=8 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\"|Notes\n|-\n|2014\n|''[[The Falling (2014 film)|The Falling]]''\n|Abbie Mortimer\n|\n|-\n|2016\n|''[[Lady Macbeth (film)|Lady Macbeth]]''\n|Katherine Lester\n|\n|-\n|2018\n|''[[The Commuter (film)|The Commuter]]''\n|Gwen\n|\n|-\n|2018\n|''[[Outlaw King]]''\n|[[Elizabeth de Burgh]]\n|\n|-\n|2018\n|''[[Malevolent (2018 film)|Malevolent]]''\n|Angela Sayers\n|\n|-\n|2019\n|''[[Fighting with My Family]]''\n|[[Paige (wrestler)|Saraya \"Paige\" Knight]]\n|\n|-\n|2019\n| ''[[Midsommar (film)|Midsommar]]''\n| Dani Ardor\n|\n|-\n|2019\n| ''[[Little Women (2019 film)|Little Women]]''\n| [[Amy March]]\n|\n|-\n|2020\n|''[[Black Widow (2020 film)|Black Widow]]''\n| [[Black Widow (Yelena Belova)|Yelena Belova / Black Widow]]\n| Post-production\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\"|Notes\n|-\n|2015\n|''Studio City''\n|Cat\n|Unaired TV pilot\n|-\n|2016\n|''[[Marcella (TV series)|Marcella]]''\n|Cara Thomas\n|3 episodes\n|-\n|2018\n|''[[King Lear (2018 film)|King Lear]]''\n|[[Cordelia (King Lear)|Cordelia]]\n|Television film\n|-\n|2018\n|''[[The Little Drummer Girl (miniseries)|The Little Drummer Girl]]''\n|Charmian \"Charlie\" Ross\n|Miniseries\n|}\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{{main|List of awards and nominations received by Florence Pugh}}\n\nPugh has received nominations for an [[Academy Awards|Academy Award]], two [[British Academy Film Awards]], and two [[Critics' Choice Movie Awards]].\n\nPugh won the British Independent Film Award for Best Actress for her performance in ''Lady Macbeth'' (2016). For her role in ''Midsommar'' (2019), she was nominated for the [[Gotham Independent Film Award for Best Actress]]. For her performance in ''Little Women'' (2019), she received nominations for the BAFTA Award for Best Actress in a Supporting Role and the Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress.\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Florence Pugh}}\n* {{IMDb name}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title = [[List of awards and nominations received by Florence Pugh|Awards for Florence Pugh]]\n|list = \n{{BIFA Award for Best Performance by an Actress in a British Independent Film}}\n{{London Film Critics Circle Award for British Actress of the Year}}\n{{Troph\u00e9e Chopard}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}